# Dining Philosophers Problem in Java with Multi-Threading

## Problem Overview

The Dining Philosophers Problem is a classic synchronization problem in computer science that illustrates the challenges of avoiding deadlock in concurrent systems. It involves five philosophers sitting around a circular table, each with a chopstick on either side. A philosopher can eat only when they have both chopsticks. The problem highlights issues like:

- Deadlock (all philosophers holding one chopstick and waiting for the other)
- Starvation (philosophers never get to eat)
- Race conditions (concurrent access to shared resources)

## Java Multi-Threading Implementation

```java
import java.util.concurrent.locks.Condition;
import java.util.concurrent.locks.ReentrantLock;
import java.util.concurrent.TimeUnit;

class Chopstick {
    private final ReentrantLock lock = new ReentrantLock();
    private final String name;

    public Chopstick(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    public void take() {
        lock.lock();
        try {
            System.out.println("Philosopher is taking " + name);
            TimeUnit.MILLISECONDS.sleep(100); // Simulate thinking time
            System.out.println("Philosopher has taken " + name);
        } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            Thread.currentThread().interrupt();
        } finally {
            lock.unlock();
        }
    }

    public void drop() {
        lock.lock();
        try {
            System.out.println("Philosopher is dropping " + name);
            TimeUnit.MILLISECONDS.sleep(100); // Simulate eating time
            System.out.println("Philosopher has dropped " + name);
        } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            Thread.currentThread().interrupt();
        } finally {
            lock.unlock();
        }
    }

    // Method to check if chopstick is available
    public boolean isAvailable() {
        return lock.tryLock();
    }

    public void release() {
        lock.unlock();
    }
}

